# Known-bad command names for the reject-obfuscated-commands hook.
# Format: name<TAB>message-suffix — the hook prints "Blocked: <name> <suffix>".
# The suffix is optional; the default is
# "is not permitted - no legitimate need for it in this workflow".
# Blank lines and #-comments are ignored. This list wins over command-allowlist.
#
# These names are rejected even though they are plain bare words, because
# each one either executes a string as new code (eval/source), re-enters a
# shell (sub-shells are banned per PR #1159 direction), or is a wrapper
# whose own flag grammar can smuggle another command past name-based checks
# (the round-7 `env -i` bypass class).

# Indirect execution
eval	used for indirect/obfuscated execution
source	is not permitted - executes a script in the current shell, hiding its commands from this check
.	is not permitted - executes a script in the current shell, hiding its commands from this check

# Sub-shells (banned outright; the interpreter re-invocation check also
# covers inline-code flags for anything later removed from this list)
bash	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow
sh	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow
dash	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow
zsh	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow
ksh	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow
mksh	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow
csh	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow
tcsh	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow
fish	is not permitted - sub-shells are banned in this workflow

# Wrapper commands that run another command (possibly behind their own
# leading flags)
